<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-284-497  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 284 497.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  January 30 1989 n402 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Government ban on Toshiba may hurt U.S. firms. (includes relatedarticle on tougher import rules)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US government sanctions against Toshiba Corp prohibit governmentpurchasers from buying Toshiba products or hiring Toshiba as aprime or sub-contractor for three years.andP;  New guidelines alsorestrict purchases of Toshiba products from intermediarycompanies, although government agencies may buy productscontaining Toshiba parts if the parts are 'substantiallytransformed.' The guidelines clarify a ban included in the 1988omnibus trade bill and put into effect Dec 28, 1988.andP;  They wereissued in a memo from the federal Office of Management and BudgetOffice of Federal Procurement Policy.andP;  The Federal AcquisitionRegulation Council is expected to publish by early Mar 1989 in theFederal Register regulations based on the guidelines.andP;  Thedefinition of 'substantially transformed' is apparently changedfrom past usage.andP;  One industry lawyer believes use of componentswill still be permissible.andP;  The US action stems from Toshibasubsidiary Toshiba Machine Co sale of secret submarine technologyto the Soviet Union.andP;  Sanctions also affect KongsbergVaapenfabrick, whose subsidiary was similarly accused.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Toshiba Corp. (export-import trade).andO;Topic:     United States. Office of Management and BudgetGovernment RegulationIntegrated CircuitsInternational TradeGovernment ContractsParts Supply.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>